            <pb n="51" facs="#f0001"/>
            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Universal Diffusion of Life.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>&#x2014;When the<lb break="yes"/>active curiosity of man is engaged in
                        interrogating<lb break="yes"/>nature, or when his imagination dwells on the
                        wide<lb break="yes"/>fields of organic creation, among the multifarious<lb
                        break="yes"/>impressions which his mind receives, perhaps none is<lb
                        break="yes"/>so strong and profound as that of the universal pro-<lb
                        break="no"/>fusion with which life is every where distributed. Even<lb
                        break="yes"/>on the polar ice the air resounds with the cries or<lb
                        break="yes"/>songs of birds, and with the hum of insects. Nor is<lb
                        break="yes"/>it only the lower dense and vaporous strata of the at-<lb
                        break="no"/>mosphere thus filled with life, but also the higher and<lb
                        break="yes"/>more etherial regions. Whenever Mont Blanc or the<lb
                        break="yes"/>summits of the Cordilleras have been ascended, living<lb
                        break="yes"/>creatures have been found there. On the Chimborazo,<lb
                        break="yes"/>8,000 feet higher than Etna, we found butterflies and<lb
                        break="yes"/>other winged insects, borne by ascending currents of<lb
                        break="yes"/>air to those almost unapproachable solitudes, which<lb
                        break="yes"/>man, led by a restless curiosity or unappeaseable thirst<lb
                        break="yes"/>of knowledge, treads with adventurous but cautious<lb
                        break="yes"/>steps; like him, strangers in those elevated regions,<lb
                        break="yes"/>their presence shows us that the more flexible organi-<lb
                        break="no"/>zation of animal creation can subsist far beyond the<lb
                        break="yes"/>limits at which vegetation ceases. The condor, the<lb
                        break="yes"/>giant of the vulture tribe, often soared over our heads<lb
                        break="yes"/>above all the summits of the Andes, at an altitude<lb
                        break="yes"/>higher than would be the Peak of Teneriffe if piled<lb
                        break="yes"/>on the snow-covered crests of the Pyrenees. The<lb break="yes"
                    />rapacity of this powerful bird attracts him to these<lb break="yes"/>regions,
                    whence his far-seeing eye may discern the<lb break="yes"/>objects of his
                    pursuit, the soft-woolled vicunas, which,<lb break="yes"/>wandering in herds,
                    frequent, like the chamois, the<lb break="yes"/>mountain pastures adjacent to
                    the regions of perpetual<lb break="yes"/>snow.&#x2014;<hi rendition="#i"
                        >Humboldt.</hi>
                </p>
            </div>
